Shan Wang 2024

Introducing Humor to Behavior Change Prompts

Increase Healthy Behavior Changes

In a world where sitting for a long time becomes increasingly common, a reminder to move is often a feature of the fitness apps to help users reach their movement goals and stay healthy. In this research study, a survey experiment was ran with 114 users to evaluate how an innovative approach of content design would persuade users to take a break and move while feeling less interrupted.

Method

Survey experiment

My role

Principal Investigator

Timeline

1 semester

Background

One day I was working in my office, I realized how long I had been sitting in front of my computer and ignored any push notifications from my Fitness apps asking me to take a break. I looked around and there were my coworkers bending over to their computers as well. With a curious mind, I found research papers from health fields. Sitting for a long time without a break is associated with many chronic diseases, including cardiovascular disease and obesity. The health researchers say that working out after work wont compensate the hurts by long sitting. How could we keep healthy then?

Normal push notifications only have limited effect and are ignored by us. Therefore, a novel approach to take a break is in need. This study proposed and valuated a novel approach to persuade people to take a break from work - using humorous prompt content in the push notifications.

Goals and Questions

Evaluate if the humorous prompts can better persuade users to take a break from work

Will humorous prompts better persuade users to move?

Evaluate if the humorous prompts can make users feel less interrupted

Will humorous prompts trigger less negative feelings?

Methods

An online survey experiment with two conditions ( humorous prompts vs. non-humorous prompts)

Rationale:

Experiment is good for evaluating effects of a factor

No device and funding support + limited time => online survey

Recruitment and Process

n = 114 left after data cleaning, recruited from Amazon Mechanical Turk

Similar gender distribution

58 read humorous prompts, 56 read non-humorous prompts

Answered questions of how much they would like to take a break from work and how much they feel interrupted ( 1 to 5 )

Insights

Add humor content to reminders and push notifications to increase effectiveness

Users who rated the prompt as funnier and more humorous, tend to take a break from work. Humor is useful to increase behavioral intention and also fits in the workplaces to reduce stress. It helps increase persuasion and increase self-efficacy, which also aligned with the research results from advertisement and health fields. Users individual preferences on humor may need to be considered.

Add humor content to increase user experience

Users who rated the prompt as funnier and more humorous, tend to feel less interrupted when receiving the prompt during work time. Humor helps the reminder or notification message to get more attention while making the content more likable. Users individual preferences on humor may need to be considered.

Personalization to take care of the individual preferences

Users have different tastes on what is humorous and what is not. We could provide personalized humorous content to make sure to satisfy users needs.

Conclusions

A novel approach of introducing humor to the prompt content of reminders and push notifications can help improve their effectiveness and provide better user experience. A humorous prompt, if users agree that its humorous, may persuade users better to take a break from stressful work environment and feel less interrupted. This approach would work great if considering users personalized humor tastes.

Reflections

If I have more time and support, I would recruit Fitbit users and gain access to their push notification system and their movement data.
